lon Habila, Measuring Time -- tAma Ata Aidoo (ed.): African Love Stories: an Anthology -- tTsitsi Dangaremgba: The Book of Not -- tMarilyn Heward Mills: Cloth Girl -- tNgûgì wa Thiong’o: Wizard of the Crow -- tChris Abani: Becoming Abigail -- tChris Dunton: Boxing and Other Stories Tunde Fatunde, Shattered Calabash -- tFlora Veit-Wild: Writing Madness: Borderlines of the Body in African Literature -- tGerd Meuer: Journeys around & with Kongi – Half a Century on the Road with Wole Soyinka -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis issue of African Literature Today focuses on new novels by emerging as well as established African novelists.This is a seminal work that discusses the validity of the perception that the new generation of African novelists is remarkably different in vision, style, and worldview from the older generation. The contention is that the oldergeneration novelists who were too close to the colonial period in Africa had invariably made culture-conflict and little else their dominant thematic concern while the younger generation novelists are more versatile in their thematic preoccupations, and are more global in their vision and style. Do the facts in the novels justify and validate these claims? The 13 papers in this volume have been carefully selected to consider these issues. Brenda Cooper a renowned literary scholar from Cape Town writes on Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's Purple Hibiscus, while Charles Nnolim writes about Adichie's more recent novel Half of a Yellow Sun; Omar Sougou of Universite GastonBerger, Senegal discusses 'ambivalent inscriptions' in Buchi Emecheta's later novels; Clement Okafor of the University of Maryland, addresses the theme of 'racial memory' in Isidore Okpewho's Call Me By My Rightful Name, juxtaposed between the world of the old and the realities of the present. Joseph McLaren, Hofstra University, New York, discusses Ngugi's latest novel, Wizard of the Crow, while Machiko Oike, Hiroshima University, Japan looksat a new theme in African adolescent literature, 'youth in an era of HIV/AIDS'. There is abundant evidence of the contrasts and diversities which characterize the African novel not only geographically, but also ideologically andgenerationally. ERNEST EMENYONU is Professor of the Department of Africana Studies University of Michigan-Flint. Nigeria: HEBN  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican literature (English)y20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAfrican literature (English)y21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / African.2bisacsh  aAfrican Literature.  aEmerging Authors.  aEstablished.  aNew Novels.1 aAkhuemokhan, Sophie I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkhuemokhan, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzodo, Ada U., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzodo, Ada Uzoamaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailly, Sery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDhar, Tej N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodgson-Katiyo, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmenyonu, Ernest N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmenyonu, Ernest N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGibbs, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManyika, Sarah Ladipo, econtrib